pull_request.title: [Bonsai] Add proper rounding of float attributes by model precision
pull_request.body:
In the `Attribute` class, `get_value` method was not properly handling `float` value attributes and simply passing them as-is, which can trigger some surprising float representation issues in Python (since it tries to represent each `float` in the highest precision).

The correct behaviour should be to round off float attributes up to the specified model precision ([documentation](https://ifc43-docs.standards.buildingsmart.org/IFC/RELEASE/IFC4x3/HTML/lexical/IfcGeometricRepresentationContext.htm)), or default to `1e-6` precision.

Additionally, here is where you'd include context about scripts which are commonly executed, such as linter and formatter scripts.
- **Repository Structure**: This section is where you'll include high level context about how the repository is laid out, any highly useful and not overly obvious information about how the directories/files are structured, different apps/packages/services inside the repository, etc. Do not include every last detail about the repository contents, only a high level technical overview on the repository structure.
- **Dependencies and Installation**: This section should include high level context about how to install dependencies, where to install them, package managers, etc. Do not include overly verbose context in this section as most repositories typically have straightforward dependency management. 
- **Testing Instructions**: A general guide on testing in this repository. It should include context such as testing frameworks, roughly what types of modules should be tested, how to run tests, and any other context a developer wouldn't be able to infer by looking at test files on how to write & run tests. Do not include every last detail about testing in this section, only the most used/important context necessary to run tests.
- **Pull request formatting**: Rules and guidelines around how to format pull request titles and descriptions. This should only be populated if you find specific instructions in the repository around how to format pull request titles and descriptions. If the repository does not have specific instructions, leave this section empty. The agent will already generate well thought out titles and descriptions, so unless there are special rules specific to this repository, leave this section empty.

The file should not contain any other content besides those tags, and the rules/context/instructions they contain. Ensure your rules are thoughtful, concise and actually useful to a developer who's never contributed to the repository before. issue.title: Excessive DEBUG logging for networked entity updates causes massive log spam
issue.body:
### Issue description

The mod generates an extreme amount of DEBUG-level logs for machine network updates, flooding `debug.log` with repetitive messages like:  

```plaintext
[Server thread/DEBUG] [oritech/]: sending networked entity update: TICK at BlockPos{x=4008, y=72, z=-56} for oritech:refinery_entity
[Server thread/DEBUG] [oritech/]: sending networked entity update: SPARSE_TICK at BlockPos{x=4040, y=72, z=-40} for oritech:foundry_entity
```

**Impact:**  
- Log files grow **100MB+ in just a few hours** with only a few machines running  
- Makes server debugging difficult due to log bloat  
- Wastes disk I/O and may affect performance  
- Impossible to share logs for troubleshooting  


Would appreciate any fix or config option to control this logging behavior. Thanks! 

### Steps to reproduce

1. Place a few Oritech machines (e.g., Refinery, Foundry)  
2. Run them for a short time (~1 hour)  
3. Check `logs/debug.log` ‚Äì it will be filled with these messages

issue.body:
Why

As a new or returning cherry user
I want to sign in with Google, Apple (iOS), Email/Password, or Facebook
So that I can securely access my account across devices

Acceptance Criteria...

Google Sign-In
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: First-time Google sign-in (success)
	‚Ä¢	Given the app is installed and the user taps ‚ÄúContinue with Google‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	When Google OAuth completes successfully
	‚Ä¢	Then the user is signed in and lands on the post-login screen with their profile created
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Google sign-in canceled
	‚Ä¢	Given the user has opened the Google auth sheet
	‚Ä¢	When the user cancels or closes the sheet
	‚Ä¢	Then the user remains signed out and sees a non-blocking ‚ÄúSign in canceled‚Äù message
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Google sign-in error
	‚Ä¢	Given the device has poor connectivity or OAuth fails
	‚Ä¢	When the flow errors
	‚Ä¢	Then the user remains signed out and sees a generic error with a ‚ÄúTry again‚Äù option
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Existing Google user
	‚Ä¢	Given the email already exists in our auth provider
	‚Ä¢	When the user signs in with the same Google account
	‚Ä¢	Then their existing profile is loaded and session starts (no duplicate profile)
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Analytics/telemetry
	‚Ä¢	Given any Google auth attempt
	‚Ä¢	When success, cancel, or error occurs
	‚Ä¢	Then an event is logged with outcome and error code (if any)

Sign in with Apple (iOS)
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: First-time Apple sign-in (success)
	‚Ä¢	Given the user taps ‚ÄúContinue with Apple‚Äù on iOS
	‚Ä¢	When Apple Sign In completes successfully (real email or Private Relay)
	‚Ä¢	Then the user is signed in and lands on post-login screen with profile created
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Apple sign-in canceled
	‚Ä¢	Given the Apple sign-in sheet is visible
	‚Ä¢	When the user cancels
	‚Ä¢	Then the user remains signed out and sees a non-blocking message
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Apple sign-in error
	‚Ä¢	Given a network or credential error
	‚Ä¢	When the flow errors
	‚Ä¢	Then the user remains signed out and sees a retry option
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Email relay stability
	‚Ä¢	Given the user uses ‚ÄúHide My Email‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	When they return on the same device or another iOS device
	‚Ä¢	Then they can sign in again and reach the same account
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Analytics/telemetry
	‚Ä¢	Log success/cancel/error with Apple-specific reason codes where available

Email & Password
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: New account ‚Äî email verification
	‚Ä¢	Given the user enters a valid email and strong password
	‚Ä¢	When they tap ‚ÄúCreate account‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Then a verification email is sent and the UI shows ‚ÄúCheck your email‚Äù state
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Email verification complete
	‚Ä¢	Given the user clicks the verification link
	‚Ä¢	When they return to the app
	‚Ä¢	Then they can sign in and reach the post-login screen
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Weak or invalid password
	‚Ä¢	Given the user enters a weak or invalid password
	‚Ä¢	When they attempt to create the account
	‚Ä¢	Then inline validation explains the issue and prevents submission
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Existing email
	‚Ä¢	Given the email is already registered
	‚Ä¢	When the user attempts to sign up
	‚Ä¢	Then they‚Äôre prompted to ‚ÄúSign in‚Äù instead (no duplicate account)
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Password reset
	‚Ä¢	Given the user taps ‚ÄúForgot password?‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	When they submit a registered email
	‚Ä¢	Then a reset email is sent and the UI confirms ‚ÄúReset link sent‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Email sign-in error handling
	‚Ä¢	Given network or invalid-credentials errors
	‚Ä¢	When the user tries to sign in
	‚Ä¢	Then descriptive, non-sensitive error feedback is shown and can retry
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Analytics/telemetry
	‚Ä¢	Log create, verify sent, verify complete, sign-in success, sign-in failure, reset sent

Facebook Login
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: First-time Facebook sign-in (success)
	‚Ä¢	Given the user taps ‚ÄúContinue with Facebook‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	When Facebook OAuth completes successfully
	‚Ä¢	Then the user is signed in and lands on post-login screen with profile created
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Facebook sign-in canceled
	‚Ä¢	Given the Facebook sheet is presented
	‚Ä¢	When the user cancels
	‚Ä¢	Then the user remains signed out and sees a non-blocking message
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Facebook sign-in error
	‚Ä¢	Given a network or provider error
	‚Ä¢	When the flow errors
	‚Ä¢	Then the user remains signed out and sees a retry option
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Existing Facebook user
	‚Ä¢	Given the email already exists
	‚Ä¢	When the user signs in with Facebook
	‚Ä¢	Then the same account is used (no duplicate), or the user is guided to link accounts if provider conflict occurs
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Analytics/telemetry
	‚Ä¢	Log success/cancel/error with provider error codes

Cross-cutting (All Providers)
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Session persistence
	‚Ä¢	Given the user successfully signs in
	‚Ä¢	When they relaunch the app within the session TTL
	‚Ä¢	Then they remain signed in without re-authenticating
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Sign out
	‚Ä¢	Given the user is signed in
	‚Ä¢	When they tap ‚ÄúSign out‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Then session is cleared and they return to the pre-login screen
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Rate limiting / lockout UX
	‚Ä¢	Given repeated failed attempts (e.g., >N within M minutes)
	‚Ä¢	When throttling/lockout happens
	‚Ä¢	Then the user sees a friendly throttle message and next-steps timing
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Accessibility
	‚Ä¢	Given the auth screen
	‚Ä¢	When using VoiceOver and large text
	‚Ä¢	Then all buttons/labels are accessible and readable
	‚Ä¢	SCENARIO: Privacy & copy
	‚Ä¢	Given any auth screen
	‚Ä¢	When displayed
	‚Ä¢	Then Terms & Privacy links are present and open successfully in-app

Proposed Implementation
	‚Ä¢	Auth provider: Use your existing auth backend (e.g., Firebase Authentication) with providers enabled for Google, Apple (iOS), Email/Password, and Facebook.
	‚Ä¢	Mobile SDKs:
	‚Ä¢	Google: platform-specific Google Sign-In SDK or Firebase Auth Google provider
	‚Ä¢	Apple (iOS): Sign in with Apple framework with nonce to prevent replay; require ‚ÄúEmail‚Äù scope
	‚Ä¢	Email/Password: built-in provider; enable email verification templates
	‚Ä¢	Facebook: Facebook Login SDK or Firebase Auth Facebook provider
	‚Ä¢	Environment/config:
	‚Ä¢	Store OAuth client IDs, Apple team/service IDs, and FB App ID in secure env (per build scheme).
	‚Ä¢	Configure URL types/redirect URIs for each provider.
	‚Ä¢	Linking accounts:
	‚Ä¢	Implement provider collision handling; offer ‚ÄúLink accounts‚Äù path when email exists with different provider.
	‚Ä¢	Emulator/Mocking (MVP):
	‚Ä¢	Use auth emulator or a mock auth layer to simulate success, cancel, and error states per provider.
	‚Ä¢	Stub network failures to validate error UI.
	‚Ä¢	Log test outcomes to a QA collection for audit.
	‚Ä¢	Analytics:
	‚Ä¢	Emit events: auth_attempt, auth_success, auth_cancel, auth_error, email_verify_sent, email_verify_complete, password_reset_sent.
	‚Ä¢	Include provider, error_code, and latency_ms.
	‚Ä¢	Test data:
	‚Ä¢	Create test accounts: google ‚úî, apple (relay) ‚úî, email_verified ‚úî/‚úñ, facebook ‚úî.
	‚Ä¢	QA checklist (manual):
	‚Ä¢	Buttons visible: Google, Apple (iOS), Email, Facebook
	‚Ä¢	Success, cancel, error flows validated for each provider
	‚Ä¢	Email verification and password reset flows validated
	‚Ä¢	Session persists across relaunch; sign-out clears state
	‚Ä¢	Accessibility: VoiceOver labels, Dynamic Type, contrast
	‚Ä¢	Terms/Privacy links function

Mainpage

Increase frameworks dependency version to 6.16

de97275a387abcbca6fcb185bcbd1b69c30f5c66 here in NeoChat depends on
de05764b4764d5641c647bb75bdf184522f63989 in Kirigami. However, that
Kirigami commit only landed in Frameworks 6.16, while the minimum
Frameworks version specified here in NeoChat's CMake remained at 6.12.

Because the CMake dependency version wasn't set to 6.16, a potential
build-time error was converted into a potential runtime error. And
that's exactly what happened for NeoChat's 25.08 Flatpak packaging,
because the KDE Runtime doesn't yet have Frameworks 6.16 in it.
